<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 16 日，星期日 18:07:59 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120</ttl><item><title><![CDATA[In Vilnius, NATO Got Two Wins and One Big Loss]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>北约终于有了一个计划。不幸的是，它不包括承认乌克兰。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Ee9GpeoagNiAOsJtTyM-cPXsnUM=/0x183:4000x2433/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1528741260/original.jpg" alt="乌克兰总统泽连斯基在维尔纽斯举行的北约会议新闻发布会上发表讲话。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>阿图尔·维达克/NurPhoto/Getty</figcaption></figure>北约维尔纽斯峰会发生了三件重要的事情：一次突破、一次鲜为人知但影响巨大的成功以及一次失望。突破在于土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安最终同意瑞典加入。这次峰会最重要的成果是批准了 4000 多页的军事计划，用于北约国家的实际防御。令人失望的是乌克兰没有获得加入北约的途径。<br><br>这一突破成为会议早期的头条新闻。埃尔多安总统几个月来一直阻止瑞典加入，要求瑞典<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sweden-must-do-more-if-it-wants-to-join-nato-turkey-says-f00b73b3?mod=article_inline">引渡约 120 名</a>被指控的库尔德工人党 (PKK) 活动人士和葛兰主义者（美国也为此与土耳其发生争执）；解除对土耳其的武器禁运；并通过更友好的反恐立法、“防止挑衅的机制”，甚至修改宪法。土耳其就其中大部分措施做出了承诺。但随后，在峰会前夕，埃尔多安<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/10/world/europe/erdogan-turkey-sweden-nato.html">又提出了另一个</a>先决条件：土耳其加入欧盟。幸运的是，有点令人惊讶的是，埃尔多安同意北约秘书长延斯·斯托尔滕贝格的交易，其中显然包括与总统乔·拜登的双边会晤、美国向土耳其交付 F-16 战斗机以及设立北约“反恐特别协调员” ”。<br><br>但对于埃尔多安来说， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/12/world/europe/erdogan-turkey-sweden-nato.html">一切都还没有结束</a>，我们可能还会看到另一轮谈判，因为瑞典法院现在（在协议宣布后） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2023/7/13/swedens-supreme-court-blocks-extradition-of-two-wanted-by-turkey">阻止了引渡</a>，而土耳其议会将在接下来的两个月内不会开会，所以是时候提出更多要求了。<br><br>维尔纽斯会议的巨大成功是通过了一项全面计划，以履行北约的基本责任——保卫其成员国的领土。该联盟自 1991 年以来就没有这样的计划。为了消除俄罗斯对将北约成员国的安全范围扩大到前华沙条约组织和前苏联国家的担忧， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thehill.com/opinion/international/3514801-nato-russia-its-time-to-suspend-the-founding-act/">北约声称</a>没有理由在该地区部署核武器或大量作战部队。新成员国。这一承诺取决于安全环境，随着俄罗斯对乌克兰的侵略，安全环境发生了巨大变化。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/nato-jens-stoltenberg-unelected-bureaucrat-ukraine/674608/">安妮·阿普尔鲍姆：多边人比普京意识到的更强大</a><br><br>在维尔纽斯通过的新计划长达<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.economist.com/international/2023/07/02/nato-is-drafting-new-plans-to-defend-europe">4,000 页</a>，这证明了其严肃性，并且北约国家政府已同意这些计划。它们允许北约军事指挥官向不同国家的部队分配特定的义务，从而在北约盟国受到攻击时促进有效的共同防御。这一安排锁定了美国及其欧洲盟国之间的责任分担，这些盟国需要通过增加军费开支以及提供自己的太空和网络资产来减少对华盛顿的依赖。<br><br>联合战争是一项微妙而艰巨的任务。提前了解盟国愿意做什么，以及他们的部队力量在哪里可以最好地满足需求，将使那些最容易受到俄罗斯潜在侵略的盟国放心，并提高所有盟国共同有效行动的能力。北约为这些计划设计、同意并拨出资源这一事实应该有助于阻止对其前线国家的攻击。<br><br>然而，维尔纽斯会议的结束却令人失望。距离俄罗斯入侵乌克兰已经过去了500多天。尽管美国和英国向乌克兰提供了武器和合作，但它们未能充分履行根据 1994 年《布达佩斯备忘录》所做出的确保乌克兰安全的承诺，以换取乌克兰放弃其核武库。与此同时，基辅一直在推动寻找加入北约的明确道路。乌克兰<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/06/03/1179979756/zelenskyy-accepts-ukraine-cannot-become-a-nato-member-until-the-war-ends">承认</a>，当该国仍处于战争状态时，不可能成为该国的成员（尽管北约过去已经找到了解决该问题的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.iiss.org/online-analysis/survival-online/2023/072/how-to-end-a-war-some-historical-lessons-for-ukraine/">创造性解决方案</a>），但希望得到承诺，一旦战争结束，它将成为该国的成员。相反，拜登总统在维尔纽斯会议之前表示， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/09/politics/joe-biden-ukraine-nato-russia-cnntv/index.html">乌克兰尚未准备好</a>加入北约。<br><br>乌克兰总统泽连斯基被激怒了。面对国家安全顾问杰克·沙利文和英国国防部长本·华莱士的断然<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ft.com/content/dc658252-6acd-44fc-8e0c-51a284009762?shareType=nongift">拒绝</a>，他发布了一条<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/ZelenskyyUa/status/1678707674811187200">愤怒的</a>推文；后者建议乌克兰应该对所给予的所有支持表示感谢。<br><br>北约国家确实大力支持乌克兰，但让安全的人们告诉那些受到攻击的人应该感激是不恰当的。拜登政府不公平地希望从其宽泛的言辞中受益——美国总统承诺“只要需要”就支持乌克兰，让乌克兰赢得战争——但又不想因其在乌克兰急需的武器问题上做出的胆怯决定而受到批评。 。例如，华盛顿仍在保留陆军战术导弹系统等远程弹药，其<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2023/07/12/biden-vilnius-nato-ukraine/">政策</a>的驱动力被<em>《华盛顿邮报》</em>描述为“坚信美国在乌克兰的失误可能引发第三次世界大战”。<br><br>拜登总统担心直接卷入战争的风险并没有错，他在将北约第五条安全保障扩展到与俄罗斯交战的国家方面也吝啬也没有错。但政府通过有效贬低乌克兰所做的一切来捍卫这些选择，无论在道义上还是在实践上都是错误的。拜登总统将美国从阿富汗撤军的失败归咎于阿富汗安全部队，而不是我们自己的政策，随意否认乌克兰加入北约的意愿，感觉就像是一回事。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2022/05/ukraine-russia-nato-jens-stoltenberg-interview/661140/">阅读：“我们不要忘记暴行，这一点极其重要”</a><br><br>北约成员资格的标准一直是主观的。 1952年希腊和土耳其入盟后发生军事政变时，他们是主观的； 1955年，分裂的德国西半部被接纳； 1982年，正在实行民主化的西班牙被接纳。根据地缘战略环境，制定并放宽了更为苛刻的标准，这些地缘战略环境为乌克兰最终的入盟提供了更鼓舞士气的前景。<br><br>失去冷静是泽连斯基在这场战争中为数不多的外交失误之一，他很快就纠正了这一错误。这位乌克兰总统<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/ZelenskyyUa/status/1679260450263818240">随后的言论</a>让人想起<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://history.state.gov/milestones/1937-1945/atlantic-conf">1941年会议</a>后温斯顿·丘吉尔的言论，当时英国希望但没有得到美国承诺打击纳粹德国：比以往任何时候都更接近，不是是否会这样，而是何时。<br><br>在北约峰会召开的同时，七国集团发表声明称，成员国将开始与乌克兰就双边安全安排进行谈判。它的目的是低于北约的承诺，但也比什么都没有。但该组织的承诺只是开始讨论——讨论那些不愿通过北约做出安全承诺的国家，以及那些未能履行其向北约做出的承诺的国家的承诺。乌克兰，1994 年。<br><br>对乌克兰继续被排除在北约之外的最好掩饰是，拜登白宫将明年举行的北约 75 周年峰会推迟了实际周年纪念日四个月，并且距离 2024 年总统大选更近，以便在政治上掀起欢迎乌克兰加入的浪潮。北约大家庭在对总统具有最大政治价值的时刻。希望白宫的政治人物不像国家安全团队那么胆怯。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 15:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/vilnius-nato-summit-sweden-turkey-ukraine/674721/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/07/vilnius-nato-summit-sweden-turkey-ukraine/674721/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Goodbye to the Prophets of Doom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>关于全球经济的传统观点是富人越来越富，穷人越来越穷。如果事实并非如此怎么办？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AAP-a5AsFwsWVsmF4hkep4tT-TU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/inequality_2/original.jpg" alt="一张美元钞票被折皱得像楼梯的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>在大衰退<span class="smallcaps">期间</span>，公众对经济的讨论经历了极大的失望。<br><br>在这个国家的大部分历史中，大多数美国人都认为未来会给他们或他们的后代带来更大的富裕。尽管经济危机时有发生，但总的情况似乎是每个阶层的人都在进步。这些期望在很大程度上得到了证实：例如，在 20 世纪中叶的大部分时间里，美国工薪阶层所享有的生活水平远远高于一两代人之前的富裕美国人所享有的生活水平。<br><br>但2008年金融危机之后，一段时期的严重经济困难以及经济学家对不平等话题的新兴趣颠覆了这些假设。经济衰退的预测占据了话题。美国这个长期以来以其根深蒂固的乐观主义而闻名的国家，开始对未来感到恐惧——现在看来，大多数人拥有的东西会越来越少。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/inflation-jobs-unemployment-recession/674593/">Adam Ozimek：差点引发经济衰退的简单错误</a><br><br>三个论点为“大失望”提供了思想基础。第一个由麻省理工学院经济学家戴维·奥托提出的颇具影响力的观点是，大多数美国人的工资在人们的记忆中第一次出现停滞。尽管在上个世纪的大部分时间里，美国人的平均收入大约每代人翻一番，但大多数人的工资增长在 20 世纪 80 年代开始趋于平稳。到 2010 年，较贫穷的美国人似乎面临着一个生活水平不再能得到任何真正改善的未来。<br><br>第二个论点与全球化对全球收入分配的影响有关。在一张后来被称为“大象曲线”的图表中，塞尔维亚裔美国经济学家布兰科·米兰诺维奇认为，世界上最贫穷的人只经历了很小的收入增长；中间百分位数从全球化中受益匪浅；那些中上层阶级——包括美国等富裕国家的许多产业工人和服务业人员——的收入停滞不前；最富有的人像强盗一样亲热。全球化似乎是一件喜忧参半的事情，而且对于美国等工业化经济体的底层工薪阶层来说，这显然是一件令人担忧的事情。<br><br>最后也是最全面的争论是关于不平等的性质和原因。尽管大部分人口刚刚维持繁荣，但最富有的美国人的财富和收入却在迅速增长。法国经济学家托马斯·皮凯蒂在 2013 年出人意料的畅销书<i>《二十一世纪的资本》</i>中提出，这种趋势可能会持续下去。皮凯蒂认为，资本的回报早已超过了劳动力的回报，他似乎暗示，只有像一场重大战争这样的灾难性事件——或者似乎不会出现的激进的政治转型——才能帮助遏制这种趋势。不平等现象日益严重。<br><br>巨大的失望继续影响着许多美国人对当前和未来经济状况的看法。但随着大流行和通货膨胀的上升改变了世界经济，这篇论文的知识基础已经开始动摇。经济悲观主义的理由开始看起来不再像以前那样令人信服。是时候修改“大失望”的核心原则了吗？<br><br>作为美国最著名的劳动经济学家<span class="smallcaps">之一</span>，奥托尔在过去十年中提供了有关美国工人收入停滞的大量证据，特别是对于那些没有大学学位的工人。<br><br>奥特尔在 2010 年一篇极具影响力的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hamiltonproject.org/publication/policy-proposal/the-polarization-of-job-opportunities-in-the-u-s-labor-market-implications-for-employment-and-earnings/">论文</a>中写道，美国经济正在出现分化。尽管对高技能工人的需求上升，但对“中等工资、中等技能的白领和蓝领工作”的需求却在萎缩。美国经济曾经提供了大量的中产阶级就业机会，现在正分裂为一个非常富裕的专业阶层和一个变得更加贫困的剩余阶层。奥托尔表示，总体结果是“非大学工人的实际收入下降”和“工资不平等急剧加剧”。<br><br>奥托过去对美国劳动力主要部分工资下降的研究使他现在听起来更加乐观，这一点更加值得注意。奥托在今年早些时候发表的一份<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://economics.mit.edu/sites/default/files/2023-03/The%20Unexpected%20Compression%20-%20Competition%20at%20Work%20in%20the%20Low%20Wage%20Labor%20Market.pdf">工作论文</a>中指出，由于公司在疫情末期拼命寻找工人，低薪工人发现自己处于更好的讨价还价地位。经济命运发生了显着逆转。<br><br> “分布底部不成比例的工资增长降低了大学工资溢价，并将自 1980 年以来总体工资不平等的上升趋势扭转了约四分之一，”奥托尔写道。近期经济趋势的大赢家正是那些在过去几十年中被排除在外的群体：“40岁以下且没有大学学位的工人的工资上涨尤其强劲。”<br><br>奥托尔表示，即使考虑到通货膨胀因素，美国底层四分之一工人的收入多年来首次出现显着增长。这位之前曾写过美国劳动力“两极分化”的学者现在得出的结论是，美国经济正在经历“意外的压缩”。换句话说，贫富差距正在以惊人的速度缩小。<br><br>一位<span class="smallcaps">作家并不是</span>唯一一位对大失望的基础产生怀疑的主要经济学家。米拉诺维奇认为，他的“大象曲线”之所以如此有影响力，部分原因是它证实了许多人对全球化影响的担忧。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.socialeurope.eu/global-income-inequality-time-to-revise-the-elephant">他现在承认</a>，他著名的图表是“对许多人想法的实证证实”。他对那条传统智慧不再那么确定了。<br><br>几年前，米兰诺维奇开始更新最初的大象曲线，该曲线基于 1988 年至 2008 年的数据。结果令人震惊——一个积极的结果。一旦 Milanovic 将下一个十年的数据纳入到 2018 年，曲线的形状就发生了变化。这条曲线的病毒性名称不再是“上升、下降、再上升”的特征，而是稳步下降的梯度现在似乎描绘了一幅简单且乐观得多的图景。在他现在调查的四十年里，世界上最贫穷的人的收入增长得非常快，中间分布的人的收入增长得相当快，而最富有的人的收入则相当缓慢。几乎每个人的全球经济状况都在改善，而且与传统观点相反，获得最大回报的是最贫困的人，而不是最富裕的人。<br><br>在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foreignaffairs.com/world/great-convergence-equality-branko-milanovic"><i>《外交事务》</i>最近发表的一篇文章</a>中，米兰诺维奇走得更远。 “我们经常被告知，”他写道，“我们生活在一个不平等的时代。”但当你查看最新的全球数据时，你会发现这是错误的：事实上，“世界正变得比 100 多年来更加平等。”<br><br><span class="smallcaps">直到今天</span>，皮凯蒂仍然是大失望的守护神。没有哪个思想家比他更频繁地被援引来证明这一理论的合理性。但即便是皮凯蒂十年前做出的悲观诊断，现在看起来也没有那么可怕了。<br><br>部分原因是皮凯蒂的研究受到了其他经济学家的批评。根据一种有影响力的论点，皮凯蒂错误地理解了为什么二战后几十年里许多工业化国家的资本回报率高于劳动力回报率。皮凯蒂认为，如果没有一致的压力来阻止这种情况发生，资本主义的本质将永远有利于亿万富翁和大公司，而不是普通工人。但根据西北大学经济学家马修·罗尼利 (Matthew Rognlie) 的说法，皮凯蒂对此的解释<i> </i>在此期间，不平等现象的加剧是由于对数据的误解。<br><br>罗格利认为，20 世纪下半叶资本回报率过高的主要原因是巴黎和纽约等大都市中心房价的大幅上涨。如果这一时期的资本回报率高于劳动回报率，那么原因不是一般的经济趋势，而是特定的政治因素，例如限制性的建筑规范。此外，主要的受益者并不是皮凯蒂所关注的亿万富翁和大企业，而是他们的利益。相反，他们是中上层专业人士，拥有大城市的大部分住房。<br><br>经济学家们仍在争论这些批评是否切中要害。但就在皮凯蒂为自己的工作辩护的同时，他本人也开始对经济的长期结构表现出更加乐观的态度。在他 2022 年出版的著作<i>《平等简史》</i>中，他将不平等的加剧视为一种异常现象。 “至少自十八世纪末以来，出现了一场争取平等的历史性运动，”他写道。 “2020 年代的世界，无论看起来多么不公正，都比 1950 年或 1900 年的世界更加平等，而后者本身在许多方面都比 1850 年或 1780 年的世界更加平等。”<br><br>与奥托尔和米拉诺维奇一样，皮凯蒂似乎也得出结论，“大失望”的论点在关键方面是错误的。<br><br>现在就消除对收入停滞或不平等加剧的担忧<span class="smallcaps">还为时过早</span>。三位前末日预言家都强调社会和政治因素在塑造经济结果中所发挥的作用。因此，他们认为最近较贫穷的美国人的工资增长部分是由唐纳德·特朗普和乔·拜登为应对这一流行病而推行的扩张性经济政策造成的。<br><br>同样，世界上一些最贫困人口近几十年来所取得的巨大成就部分归功于其政府利用产业政策来塑造全球化对其国家影响的努力。正如皮凯蒂所说，从长远来看，资本回报是否会超过劳动力回报，取决于有关税收和再分配、工会实力和劳动力市场规则的政治决策。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/labor-shortage-low-unemployment-inflation/674263/">奥伦·卡斯：劳动力短缺的神话</a><br><br>最近关于我们经济前景的好消息不应让我们得出可能很快就会变得过于乐观的结论。但我们也应该避免使本能的悲观主义持续下去，这种悲观主义看起来越来越没有道理。尽管悲观主义可能看起来很聪明或精明，但对我们建设更美好世界的集体能力的愤世嫉俗只会让我们更难为创造未来所需的经济政策赢得支持。<br><br>进步主义者有时似乎相信，他们可以通过让未来看起来可怕来动员人们。但当选民感到受到威胁时，通常是不择手段的反动派做出不切实际的承诺，并把受益的局外人当作替罪羊。工资停滞和不平等加剧仍然是我们必须保持警惕的真正危险，但更美好的经济未来看起来更容易实现这一事实应该值得大肆庆祝。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Canceled Comedy Gem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>艾伦·泰勒的娱乐必备<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/BHOk5GUq5x1xS0XjNNT8BVyz-I0=/0x0:4217x2372/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/TCDJOPE_EC004_1/original.jpg" alt="乔·佩拉挥手" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>约翰·诺瓦克 / Adult Swin / 埃弗雷特</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>欢迎回到《每日邮报》的周日文化版，一位<i>大西洋月刊的</i>作家在其中揭示了是什么让他们开心。今天的特邀嘉宾是我们的照片编辑艾伦·泰勒 (Alan Taylor)，他在<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>任职期间发表了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/our-photo-editors-must-see-images/673521/">2,000 多篇照片文章</a>。<i> </i>艾伦最近整理了人类和动物<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-keeping-cool-during-heat-waves/674606/">在热浪中保持凉爽</a>的照片，以及一些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-shark-ocean-beach/674623/">鲨鱼奇妙生活</a>的照片。<br><br>艾伦希望另一个平台能够接手被取消的订单<b> </b><i>乔·佩拉 (Joe Pera) 与你交谈</i>，在<i>《最后生还者》</i>中令人痛心的一集落泪，并了解 Bluesky 和 ​​Threads 等新社交网络平台的氛围。<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的三篇周日读物：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/old-age-personality-brain-changes-psychology/674668/">老年时期奇怪的性格变化</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/the-terrible-downside-of-ai-language-translation/674687/">在为时已晚之前学习一门外语。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-dome-southwest-arizona/674689/">西南地区什么时候变得不适宜居住？</a></li><strong>文化调查：艾伦·泰勒</strong><br><br><b>我最近读过的最好的小说：</b>我很晚才发现这些，但最近我在玛莎·威尔斯的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-murderbot-diaries-all-systems-red-artificial-condition-rogue-protocol-exit-strategy-martha-wells/9781250784278?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《谋杀机器人日记》</i></a>系列中度过了最美好的时光。 Murderbot 的冒险故事吸引了我，每一本书都比前一本更好。<br><br><b>我喜欢一首安静的歌曲，也喜欢一首响亮的歌曲：</b>安静的歌曲：佐伊·基廷<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5oawMWi_L8">(Zoë Keating) 的“Sun Will Set”</a> 。这首歌是如此美妙——不知何故既令人难忘又令人振奋。这是凉爽的秋夜里温暖篝火的味道。<br><br>响亮的歌曲： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lh_wesEZtKM">Russian Circles 的《Conduit》</a> 。这是纯粹的驱动力，一系列强大的吉他连复段、贝斯和鼓声，我很想现场听到。<br><br><b>我现在最喜欢的电视节目：</b>第一季已经结束，但我真的很喜欢 Apple TV+ 上的<i>Silo</i> 。我几年前读过这些书，记得很喜欢它们，但我忘记了很多细节。该系列确实保留了整体感觉，而且表演也很棒。丽贝卡·弗格森、科曼和蒂姆·罗宾斯确实很突出。<br><br>另外，我希望有人能拿起<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.adultswim.com/videos/joe-pera-talks-with-you"><i>《乔·佩拉与你交谈》</i></a> ，该剧在三季后被取消——它独特地有益健康、吸引人、有趣，有时甚至令人感动。 <b>[相关：</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/12/25-best-television-episodes-2018/577996/"><b>2018年25部最佳电视剧</b></a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我最喜欢的大片和最喜欢的艺术电影：</b>我将在这里给出我最简单的答案。最喜欢的大片：<i>星球大战</i>。这是最初的大片。当我 9 岁时，我在电影院多次观看了第一部电影，它以一种我从未想过的方式震撼了我。<br><br>最喜欢的艺术电影：我不知道它到底算不算“艺术电影”，但我最喜欢的充满安静之美和敬畏的电影是1983年的<i>《狼来了》</i> 。里面有很多伟大的时刻，比如主角泰勒吹着巴松管呼唤狼群，或者一架小飞机飞走时的褪色图像所暗示的孤独深度，留下泰勒独自站在加拿大偏远北极地区结冰的湖中央荒野。<br><br><b>一位对我来说意义重大的音乐艺术家：</b>几年前，当我认为听到新的重摇滚音乐的日子已经过去时，我发现了鹈鹕乐队并深入研究了它的目录，感受到了重新发现一种流派的喜悦。近年来，诸如<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RQtzU1Cxc6g">“Deny the Absolute”</a>之类的歌曲为我提供了很多动力。<br><br><b>最后一个让我落泪的娱乐节目：</b>我这几天真是太软了，一瞬间就泪流满面。也就是说，最近一部让我努力忍住不哭的节目是<i>《最后生还者》</i> ，特别是第三集“好久好久”。我也喜欢这款电子游戏，并且已经玩过好几次了，但这实际上与该集的力量以及尼克·奥弗曼和默里·巴特利特令人难以置信的故事和表演无关。即使写下它也让我哽咽。 <b>[相关：</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/01/the-last-of-us-hbo-tv-series-review/672690/"><b><i>《最后生还者》</i>让世界末日再次焕然一新</b>。</a> <b>]</b><br><br><b>我生命中的一个孩子向我介绍了一些令人愉快的事情：</b>我们的孩子几年前开始观看<i>《阿凡达：最后的气宗》</i> <i>。</i>我和我的妻子加入了他们，很快就沉浸在整个系列中——精彩的故事讲述，伟大的角色（Iroh 叔叔是最棒的）。<br><br><b>我喜欢的一位在线创作者</b><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/@ItchyBoots">“Itchy Boots”也被称为 Noraly</a> ，她骑着摩托车环游世界，独自旅行，熟练地制作视频记录几乎所有事情，包括平凡的边境口岸和翱翔的全景无人机镜头。她对许多地方的生活和风景进行了深入的了解，提供了有趣的背景信息，寻找当地的故事和经历，并且总体上良好而开朗的态度帮助她度过了有时困难的环境。<br><br><b>我回顾的一行诗或散文：</b>科马克·麦卡锡的<i>《路》</i>的最后一段。我在心里反复思考了很多次。言语和措辞是如此令人回味；自己读或大声朗读是一种乐趣，这是一种简洁的伟大练习，总结了之前整部小说的影响。<br><br> “从前，山里的小溪里有溪鳟鱼。你可以看到它们站在琥珀色的水流中，鳍的白色边缘在水流中轻轻地摆动。它们在你手里有青苔的味道。抛光、肌肉发达且抗扭。它们的背上有蠕虫状的图案，这些图案是正在形成的世界的地图。地图和迷宫。一件无法挽回的事情。不再被纠正。在他们居住的幽深峡谷中，一切事物都比人类更古老，并且充满神秘色彩。” <b>[相关：</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/06/cormac-mccarthy-author-death-blood-meridian-passenger/674398/"><b>科马克·麦卡锡之死</b></a><b>]</b><br><br><b>我最喜欢在手机上浪费时间的方式是：</b>有一款名为<i>Holedown</i>的游戏，你只需瞄准球来打破方块。这是最无需动脑、最简单的游戏，而我却花了相当多的时间来玩它。最近的另一个最爱：我一直在从 Twitter 跳到 Bluesky 再到 Threads，了解新地方的氛围，发现自己对社区之间的差异以及人们在每个平台上展示自己的方式着迷。<br><br><b>我珍视的绘画、雕塑或其他视觉艺术作品：</b>我曾经经常玩<i>《耻辱》</i>电子游戏。我非常喜欢整体的视觉美感：角色、城市街道、墙上的艺术品。其中一个关卡的一个房间里有一幅画，我觉得非常棒，一时兴起，我问我的妻子克里斯（她正处于油画阶段）是否可以复制这幅画。她做得非常出色！它现在挂在我的办公室里，我确实很珍惜它。<br><br><strong>未来一周</strong><br><br><li>两个都<b> </b><a href="https://www.barbie-themovie.com/"><i>芭比</i></a>和<a href="https://www.oppenheimermovie.com/"><i>奥本海默</i></a>在周五的票房大战中首次亮相。</li><li> <a href="https://www.peacocktv.com/stream-tv/love-island?cid=2306orglvisldpkpdsearch13133&amp;utm_campaign=2306orglvisld&amp;utm_source=pk_ggl_gglsa&amp;utm_medium=pd_search_nonbr_srcpy&amp;utm_term=144399_d62104d&amp;utm_content=144399_d62104d_144399_d62104d&amp;gclid=CjwKCAjw-7OlBhB8EiwAnoOEkxzejJizU3CqRhmb8PuLw5FGBRE85GbIh2-rg0AjLdHW3Sg_swrJcxoCnMgQAvD_BwE&amp;gclsrc=aw.ds"><i>《美国爱情岛》</i></a>第五季，参与者在热带别墅中寻找爱情，观众在家投票决定他们的命运（《孔雀星期二》首播）</li><li> <a href="https://tertulia.com/book/crook-manifesto-colson-whitehead/9780385545150?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《克鲁克宣言》</i></a> ，两届普利策奖得主科尔森·怀特海德的<a href="https://tertulia.com/book/harlem-shuffle-colson-whitehead/9780525567271?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《哈莱姆洗牌》</i></a>续集（周二发售）</li><strong>散文</strong><br><br>你从未听说过的最伟大的博物馆<br><br><em>卡伦·墨菲</em><br><br><p>在米兰安布罗修图书馆的地下室，一位名叫维托·米洛 (Vito Milo) 的管理员刚刚在一幅有 500 年历史的图画边缘涂了一条小凝胶条，以溶解将其连接到更大纸框上的胶水。现在，他用手术刀将图画松开了几毫米。我问米洛凝胶里有什么，在他用意大利语列出了一份成分清单后，我提供了一个外行人的粗略翻译：“特殊酱汁”。他微笑着点点头。 “<i>嚓</i>，特制酱料。”</p><p>这幅画是列奥纳多·达·芬奇<i>《大西洋手抄本》</i>中的一页，我受邀见证了它的艰苦保存过程。去年冬天的一个早晨，我来到了文物保护实验室，实验室位于通往安布罗修博物馆闪闪发光的金库的钢玻璃门外的一个房间。在楼梯底部，一名服务员拦住了我，他从我手中接过咖啡杯，并将其放在安全的地方。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/biblioteca-ambrosiana-milan-art-da-vinci-drawings/674625/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><strong>更多文化内容</strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/">请多看一些带有狂野性爱场面的喜剧。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/speak-now-better-than-revenge-taylor-swift-album-rerecording/674671/">为青少年泰勒·斯威夫特伸张正义</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/insidious-the-red-door-2023-movie-review/674678/">PG-13 恐怖系列，经久不衰</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/bts-book-beyond-the-story-memoir/674657/">BTS 是如何做到的</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/shakespeare-in-love-movie-creativity-modernity/674632/"><i>莎士比亚恋爱中</i>的日常天才</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/the-league-negro-leagues-review/674670/">黑人联盟如何塑造现代棒球</a></li><strong>赶上<em>大西洋</em></strong><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-climate-crises-natural-disasters/674700/">气候变化现在比以往任何时候都更加真实。</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/threads-sign-up-fomo/674696/">互联网上的 FOMO 从未如此严重过。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/covid-lab-leak-congress-investigation/674690/">共和党实验室泄漏马戏团提出了一个重要观点。</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/national-debt-fiscal-trajectory/674665/">事实证明，债务毕竟很重要。</a></li><strong>相片集</strong><br><br>纽约市的蛇颈龙化石、乌克兰的库帕拉之夜庆祝活动以及我们编辑精选的本周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-week-fire-bull-lava-flow-ice-cave/674698/">最佳照片</a>中的更多内容。<br><br> <i data-stringify-type="italic">Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">探索我们所有的时事通讯。</a></em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/joe-pera-tv-recommendations/674718/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/joe-pera-tv-recommendations/674718/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Delivery Apps Just Did the Impossible]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>硅谷正在用自己的游戏打败多米诺骨牌。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AGu-O9jBTio589Oh61_Rq-CVEfE=/0x0:5337x3002/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_492047870/original.jpg" alt="顶部带有多米诺骨牌标志的送货车" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>丹尼尔·阿克/彭博/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>近年来，达美乐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">有时</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">自诩为</a>一家以送<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">披萨</a>为副业的科技公司。这是真的。通过改进人工智能、GPS、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/06/17/dominos-will-start-delivering-pizzas-via-an-autonomous-robot-this-fall/">自动驾驶汽车</a>和增强现实等技术，全球最大的披萨连锁店将送餐这一黑暗艺术变成了一门科学。这一切都始于其著名的 Pizza Tracker，该产品于 2008 年推出，并创建了跟踪食品配送的早期标准。 Domino&#39;s 现在有大约<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">15 种不同的</a>披萨订购<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">方式</a>，包括语音助手、Facebook Messenger、Slack 和一个<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/4283913/dominos-zero-click-ordering-app/">“零点击”应用程序</a>，可在 10 秒后自动为您订购。<br><br>所有这些技术帮助达美乐增加了销售额并简化了运营，使其最终<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/25/why-pizza-hut-is-struggling-to-against-dominos-and-papa-johns.html">“超越了小屋披萨”</a> ，成为美国<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">约</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">三分之一</a>披萨外卖的服务商。其他餐厅，无论是披萨店还是其他餐厅，都已经开始依赖一系列第三方应用程序，而达美乐则将一切都保留在内部，这意味着它处于领先地位 - 从理论上讲，您也是如此。没有邮递员，没问题：只需<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.dominos.com/en/pages/order/#!/checkout/">9.99 美元左右</a>，加上少量费用和小费，多米诺 (Domino) 司机就会送出一份达美乐 (Domino) 披萨，30 分钟内就会送到您家门口。<br><br>但本周早些时候，达美乐<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">宣布</a>它也将与一款送货应用程序合作。到 2023 年底，大多数地方的饥饿群众将能够通过 Uber Eats 订购达美乐 (Domino) 馅饼和各种钠炸弹（尽管达美乐 (Domino) 的司机仍将送餐）。通过与 Uber 联手，该公司承认 DoorDash、Uber Eats 和 Grubhub 等外卖应用程序已成为主导地位——使用它们已接近餐厅维持生计的必要要求。如果 Domino&#39;s 都无法摆脱送货应用程序，那么还有谁可以呢？<br><br>恰如其分的是，美国的送餐热潮实际上是从达美乐开始的。该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/27/business/pizza-s-home-delivery-war.html">经常被认为</a>推广了披萨外卖的概念（ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">它</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">创造了现代披萨盒</a>，联合创始人汤姆·莫纳汉甚至在送披萨时<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/02/19/the-deliverer">遇见了他的妻子</a>）。尽管披萨订购从固定电话和手机转向通过移动应用程序拨号，但以送货为中心的多米诺骨牌模式却拥有惊人的寿命。 2011 年，时任首席执行官帕特里克·多伊尔 (Patrick Doyle) 开始了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://pizzaturnaround.com/">一场不太可能的全国性广告活动，</a>承认他的披萨有点糟糕，不久后，他向他的技术团队<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncr.com/blogs/restaurants/digital-innovations-dominos">发出了挑战</a>：他希望订购披萨变得足够简单，以便有人可以在等待时完成。在红绿灯处。移动点餐是未来，未来，披萨点餐只需 17 秒。<br><br>从某种意义上说，达美乐已经成为其自身成功的受害者。该公司的技术悟性帮助公众做好了不仅仅是披萨外卖的准备。这些第三方应用程序出现在 2010 年代零工经济繁荣时期，然后在疫情早期爆发。随着疫情放缓，食品配送销售本可以重蹈 Peloton 的覆辙，但<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www2.deloitte.com/us/en/pages/consumer-business/articles/future-of-restaurants-study.html">事实并非如此</a>。去年，大约 14% 的披萨销量是通过外卖应用程序<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">完成的</a>，此外还有一系列让餐厅菜单看起来平淡无奇的菜肴和美食。截至 2023 年，数十万家餐厅都使用了外卖应用，提供高级餐厅的干式熟成牛排和麦当劳的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">干式牛排百吉饼</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">。</a>餐厅的餐厅可能会再次爆满，但这些应用程序<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://secondmeasure.com/datapoints/food-delivery-services-grubhub-uber-eats-doordash-postmates/">现在带来的收入比以往任何时候都多</a>。<br><br>换句话说，它们已经变得太大而不容忽视。尽管达美乐将继续提供自己的披萨，但其首席执行官拉塞尔·韦纳 (Russell Weiner) 在讨论 Uber Eats 优食交易时，用简单的语言<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.restaurantbusinessonline.com/financing/dominos-uber-eats-deal-acknowledges-reality-third-party-marketplace">表达了错过的成本</a>：“聚合平台上发生了 50 亿美元的披萨销售额……[那]我们应该有三分之一。”<br><br>随着数以百万计的餐厅员工准备订单和数以百万计的零工为他们送货，整个送餐生态系统已经合并，这对餐厅和整个餐饮文化都产生了巨大的影响。这些应用程序可以向餐厅收取<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">高达</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">30% 的</a>费用，这给利润本来就很紧张的企业带来了沉重的负担，需要大量的订单量才能实现收支平衡。他们拥有如此大的权力，以至于他们现在正在影响<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://get.grubhub.com/blog/delivery-menu-tips/">餐馆的菜单</a>，有时即使你在里面用餐。与此同时，承担所有这些职能的送货员仍然作为独立承包商获得低工资，没有任何保护或讨价还价的能力。<br><br>对于食客来说，将科技进一步引入餐饮业是有成本的。根据 2021 年的一份报告，食品配送应用程序与社交媒体巨头<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/social-media-and-food-delivery-apps-sell-the-most-personal-data">并驾齐驱</a>，成为消费者个人数据的最大收集者和兜售者。多米诺<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">自己承认</a>，Uber 愿意交出客户数据是其决定与该公司达成协议的关键因素。即使在沙发上订购任何东西变得更加容易和方便，外卖应用程序将继续迫使餐厅调整其运营以适应他们的需求。无论您每天晚上都订购送货服务还是根本没有使用过应用程序，这一点都很重要。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why YIMBY Righteousness Backfires]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>将郊区居民视为可恨的势利小人并不会让他们更欢迎新来者。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/owUJAAHGITBEG0A2viEAgvjioqE=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/YIMBY/original.jpg" alt="加利福尼亚州安提阿的郊区房屋" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>杰森·亨利 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure>如果想要生活在一个主要居民能够轻松负担过高房价的田园社区是错误的，那么大多数美国人也不想是对的。<br><br>这是YIMBY（“Yes in My Backyard”）运动面临的核心挑战，该运动是一个由学者、政策制定者和草根活动家组成的意识形态多元化的组织，致力于一个简单得令人解除武装的想法，即在美国最繁荣的城镇建造新家园将是一件非常好的事情。作为一个智力项目，YIMBYism 取得了巨大的成功，这是有充分理由的。大量证据表明，增加住房供应以满足住房需求可以 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/mac.20170388">促进经济增长</a>并<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.urban.org/sites/default/files/publication/103472/why-housing-matters-for-upward-mobility-evidence-and-indicators-for-practitioners-and-policymakers.pdf">刺激向上流动</a>。甚至有初步证据表明，遏制当地土地使用监管可能有助于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://corinnelow.github.io/LafortuneLow.pdf">扭转工薪阶层家庭婚姻的崩溃</a>，这可不是一件小事。在研究地方土地利用的经济学家和法律学者中，关于分区改革的争论<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3917621">基本上已经结束</a>。<br><br>然而，YIMBY 运动未能克服选民根深蒂固的怀疑，他们凭直觉认为新家园意味着新邻居，而新邻居可能意味着新的麻烦。<br><br>以加利福尼亚州为例，YIMBY 立法者在那里取得了最大的进步。自 2016 年以来，加利福尼亚州立法机构通过了一系列措施，以取代当地一些最恶劣的土地使用法规，促使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/10/california-accessory-dwelling-units-legalization-yimby/671648/">附属住宅单元</a>蓬勃发展。但是，尽管有无可争议的证据表明住房负担能力危机仍在迫使数十万低收入和中等收入家庭离开该州，但许多加州人强烈反对最近的住房推动，以至于出现了真正的危险是选民将在 2024 年通过一项<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ourneighborhoodvoices.com/">投票措施</a>来推翻改革。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/california-single-family-zoning-housing/673758/">耶路撒冷德姆萨斯：加州并不特别</a><br><br>为了理解为什么加州选民如此难以赢得支持，陈·扎克伯格倡议（Chan Zuckerberg Initiative）是 YIMBYism 的主要慈善倡导者之一，委托开展了一系列焦点小组和调查，最终于去年发布了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://chanzuckerberg.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/CZI-The-California-Dream-Housing-White-Paper.pdf?_hsmi=202158258&amp;_hsenc=p2ANqtz-8dQATs5ekYbaqhSew-av8OArDJ7C4yOHPrIUsuYhkhO1dam2ool1Zxkycq6j036i1tXC4bn1DOSIMaxaVITCf_Crl2SrOS70pC7rP7s8X1jQ_TpxA">一份报告</a>。作者表示，“我们听到的大多数租客和业主都表示，他们对附近的经济适用房解决方案持谨慎态度，担心这会导致犯罪、噪音、垃圾、非法倾倒以及普遍缺乏财产维护。 ”此外，尽管绝大多数受访者“广泛接受多样性作为其社区当前或理想的特征”，但他们对邻居比他们贫穷得多的想法深感不安。<br><br>这种怀疑并不是金州独有的。今年 1 月，州长凯西·霍赫尔 (Kathy Hochul) 公布了“纽约住房契约”，这是一套雄心勃勃的改革措施，旨在提高纽约市及其臭名昭著的昂贵郊区的住房生产。到五月， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://manhattan.institute/article/nyc-housing-crisis-next-steps-after-new-york-housing-compact-fails">住房契约已经失效</a>。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/local-government-power-nimby-denver/674164/">科罗拉多州</a>、亚利桑那州和德克萨斯州的全州分区改革提案也以失败告终。<br><br>这一切并不意味着 YIMBY 主义注定要失败。但如果 YIMBY 想要推动更多美国人朝他们的方向发展，他们最好少些威吓，多些倾听。<br><br>一些最热心的 YIMBY 坚信自己的正义，采取了道德姿态，谴责顽固的房主是势利者或偏执狂，并呼吁采取全面的立法措施，剥夺地方政府的土地使用权，并进一步限制房东的能力。选择他们的租户。理查德·卡伦伯格的新书《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Excluded-Zoning-NIMBYism-Class-Build/dp/1541701461"><em>排除》</em></a>是这种情感的完美升华。<br><br>卡伦伯格以其对精英大学种族偏好的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/10/supreme-court-harvard-affirmative-action-legacy-admissions-equity/671869/">逆向批评</a>而闻名，他将自己的公共生活奉献给了种族和经济融合的论证。排除者并不满足于对可能会吸引房主自身利益的排他性分区提出审慎的理由，<em>他们</em>认为这种做法是一种道德上的愤怒——阶级主义，也隐含着种族主义——我们需要一场道德运动来根除它。联邦政府全力出动，仿照上个世纪反对种族隔离的斗争。为此，卡伦伯格呼吁制定一项经济公平住房法案，允许对歧视穷人或对不同阶层产生不必要的不​​同影响的分区政策提出诉讼，并由法官决定什么是必要的。这实际上相当于联邦政府对单户住宅分区的禁令，也会威胁到无数其他分区政策，并且在很大程度上通过基于模糊、主观的法律标准威胁提起昂贵的诉讼来威慑地方政府。<br><br>虽然这一论点肯定会引起一些社会正义进步人士的共鸣，但不太可能说服那些担心社区变化前景的焦虑的房主和租客。加州大学戴维斯分校土地使用法教授克里斯·埃尔门多夫警告说，将分区改革视为经济正义问题可能会适得其反。今天的富裕郊区居民可能会对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/race-and-zoning">他们犯有种族敌意的说法感到不满</a>，但他们完全乐意被指控为色盲阶级偏见。<br><br>反对在自家后院修建新住房的人可能不是特别开明，但他们也不是妄想。顾名思义，排他性分区是一种通过部署地方土地使用监管来吸引富裕居民并阻止贫困居民来改善地方税基的策略。美国的地方公共服务主要由地方财产税和其他市政收入（例如销售税、停车费和污水处理费）提供资金。人们不必是一个可恨的势利小人，也能认识到，虽然一些新来者在当地创造的收入会多于他们在服务中获得的收入，但其他人却不会。<br><br>事实上，这些地方财政压力可以说是塑造美国支离破碎的大都市地理的核心力量。正如普林斯顿大学经济学家利亚·布斯坦（Leah Boustan） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://press.princeton.edu/books/hardcover/9780691150871/competition-in-the-promised-land"><em>在《应许之地的竞争》一书中</em></a>指出的那样，战后时代的“白人逃亡”在很大程度上是由这些财政问题驱动的。随着贫穷的黑人移民前往东北部、中西部和西部的城市中心，大量富裕的白人家庭搬到平均收入高于他们离开的城市的郊区管辖区。毫无疑问，这种向外移民的部分原因是白人不愿与黑人邻居一起生活，但由于这一时期美国城市的隔离程度如此之高，大部分逃亡者都来自纯白人社区。城市居民离开这些白人社区的动机不是担心与黑人邻居进行社会交往，而是担心与有不同需求和优先事项的低收入邻居进行财政交往。 “搬到郊区，”布斯坦写道，“让白人家庭能够将自己与中心城市提供的不断变化的当地公共产品和财政义务隔离开来。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2015/07/white-flight-alive-and-well/399980/">阅读：白色飞行从未结束</a><br><br>鉴于这些强大的财政激励措施，小型郊区司法管辖区的邻避主义几乎是不可避免的。与其指望道德劝说能够改变这些社区的分区政策，YIMBY 人最好采取一种更加谦虚和现实的方法，努力与郊区的邻避者相向而行。<br><br>赢得郊区房主的青睐的一个直接方法是推进住房改革，帮助他们积累财富，正如埃尔门多夫<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.city-journal.org/article/the-housing-treadmill">所建议的</a>那样。例如，附属住宅单元的合法化可以让普通房主富裕起来，无论公平与否，普通房主都比大型开发商享有更多的公众同情，并且可以动员他们反对成本增加的市政影响费和自由裁量审查程序。作为额外的好处，这种改革让 YIMBY 能够在尊重财产权和个人自由的基础上发出<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.city-journal.org/article/where-are-all-the-republican-yimbys">更加乐观的呼吁</a>，这一主张帮助俄勒冈州、犹他州和蒙大拿州通过了分区改革法律。<br><br>当面对坚决的郊区阻力时，例如在纽约州南部，霍赫尔的住房契约被证明是一个巨大的政治负担，YIMBYs 应该集中精力放松大城市的土地使用监管。在人口较多的司法管辖区，对住房建设的反对往往不那么强烈，部分原因是这些地区的贫富居民比例从定义上来说更难改变。城市社区也比郊区社区更具活力：其中租房者、年轻人、低收入家庭和其他住房流失率高于平均水平的人口比例过高。社区变化是这些社区生活的一个事实。如果城市核心区的分区改革取得成功，那么较小社区的住房增长将更加引人注目。<br><br>冒着激怒反商业进步人士的风险，YIMBY 还应该采取更多措施<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/full/10.1146/annurev-polisci-051921-102505">培养大型雇主作为政治盟友</a>。较低的住房成本是吸引和留住工人的有力工具，大型雇主可以对州立法机构施加重大影响。加州科技行业的雇主在反对严格分区的斗争中发挥了重要作用并非巧合——他们敏锐地意识到，随着金州住房成本的上涨，他们要么支付更高的工资，要么眼睁睁地看着他们的工人逃往城市在爱达荷州或内华达州。<br><br>最后，YIMBY 应该努力软化最初推动排斥性分区的地方财政激励措施。耶鲁大学法学院的扎卡里·利斯考 (Zachary Liscow) 发现， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nyulawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/NYULawReview-92-6-Liscow.pdf">当各州承担更大比例的学校经费时</a>，富人会变得更愿意搬到较贫穷的司法管辖区，可能是因为这样做将不再让他们承担为大量学生提供支持服务的特殊负担。纳税很少的邻居。与这种模式一致，他发现集中的学校经费导致低收入城市的税收降低。<br><br>类似的逻辑也适用于国家对治安和公共安全工作的资助。如果邻避者担心低收入移民的涌入会导致犯罪和骚乱激增，正如陈·扎克伯格研究所的调查结果强烈表明的那样，那么增加国家对当地执法机构的援助可能会减轻他们的担忧。一些主要的社交媒体左派人士不以为然地将这种支持分区改革和“破窗”监管的结合称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://darrellowens.substack.com/p/whos-who-the-dictionary-of-in-my">监狱城市化</a>”，但社交媒体左派当然不是目标受众。<br><br>诚然，改变地方财政激励措施将是一项重大任务，这将遭到选民的抵制，他们担心在新的财政分配下会失败。但地方政府收入的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.urban.org/policy-centers/cross-center-initiatives/state-and-local-finance-initiative/state-and-local-backgrounders/state-and-local-revenues#local">30%</a>已经以州政府转移支付的形式出现。增加州政府为地方警务或公共教育提供资金的责任将是一个相对温和且可能非常受欢迎的变化，特别是与强制生产受契约限制的经济适用住房和其他优先事项的公平份额要求相比。 YIMBY 离开了。<br><br>修改地方财政激励措施、与地区商业精英结成联盟、帮助一些拥有丰富房产的房主变得更富有，不会带来一个从东海岸到西海岸的综合社区的平等新千年，但它将帮助 YIMBY 建立一个更有说服力的案例住房增长符合郊区居民开明的自身利益，否则他们可能会担心税收负担上升和房价下跌。这不是一个糟糕的开始。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/yimby-california-social-justice-kahlenberg/674714/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/yimby-california-social-justice-kahlenberg/674714/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Raunchy Comedy’s Subtle Wisdom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> <em>Joy Ride</em>知道，回国探亲并不是缓解家里孤独感的简单方法。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/6DFmKkJYZXtH8GYGMiig1wpay1k=/0x92:3000x1780/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/joyride_unit_210927_00234rc2/original.jpg" alt="《欢乐之旅》中，中国花园里的四位女性看着银幕之外的场景" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>艾德·阿拉克尔 / 狮门影业</figcaption></figure>诚然，我对<em>Joy Ride表示怀疑。</em>过去几年，典型好莱坞类型的亚裔美国电影越来越多，例如浪漫喜剧、超级英雄大片和慢热剧情片。很多都非常出色，有些则不是那么出色，但在其中几部中，我注意到一个反复出现的主题：主角过于理想化地回到亚洲。一部关于亚裔美国被收养者和她的朋友们去中国<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/">的新电影</a><em>《欢乐之旅》</em>似乎准备重演这一比喻。<br><br>但当影片上映 20 分钟时，当我因震惊和笑声而气喘吁吁时，我明白它正在做一些不同的事情。当奥黛丽（阿什利·帕克饰）来到中国时，我更感触到了这一点，并感叹每个人都长得像她。乍一看，你不是一个引人注目的少数群体，这种感觉被赋予了权力，这是关于侨民返乡的电影中相当典型的观察结果。但还没等奥黛丽兴奋起来，她最好的朋友兼旅伴洛洛（雪莉可乐饰）指出，机场里有来自台湾和中国大陆的人，还有光鲜亮丽的韩流明星，他们绕过了海关——而且它们都明显不同。奥黛丽可能会想把这些亚洲面孔视为可以互换的，这样她就能有归属感；洛洛暗示这是一个幻想，而不是现实。<br><br>这也是向观众传达的信息：<em>欢乐之旅</em>有兴趣承认——然后揭开——我所说的祖国比喻。我在过去几年的电影中特别注意到这一点，其中一个亚裔美国人角色前往亚洲，尽管它可以跨文化存在。也许主角是飞往新加坡去见他们富有的男朋友的家人，就像<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/08/asian-americas-great-gatsby-moment/568213/"><em>《疯狂的亚洲富人</em></a>》（ <em>Joy Ride</em>的导演兼联合编剧阿黛尔·林 (Adele Lim) 也是这部电影的联合编剧）那样。也许他们正在执行一项奇幻的超级英雄任务，就像漫威的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2021/08/shang-chi-legend-ten-rings-marvel-review/619867/"><em>《上气与十环传奇》</em></a>中那样。或者也许他们在韩国街头街头卖艺，爱上了当地狂躁的精灵梦中女孩，就像安静的独立电影<em>《小说与其他现实》中那样。</em>无论出于何种原因，角色们都通过亚洲之旅来了解自己。有时，祖国比喻可以成为承载主角情感转变的有效结构。但最糟糕的是，它把亚洲国家变成了亚裔美国人主角解决他们在美国的疏远或孤独问题的场所，但却没有将这些国家视为具有自身复杂性或多样性的地方。人们可能会开始觉得这些角色在他们自称是自己的人中间<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2010/08/18/129254808/eat-pray-love-leave-orientalism-still-big-onscreen"><em>“吃、祈祷、爱”</em></a> 。<br><br>以祖国比喻的基石为例：返乡蒙太奇。在<em>《摘金奇缘》</em>中，主角夫妇尼克和瑞秋在新加坡降落后，被带到了一个夜市，友好的邻里阿姨叔叔们一边对他们微笑，一边熟练地准备美味的沙爹和叻沙。在<em>《上气》</em>中，亚裔美国主角在澳门上演了主题相同的场景，飞驰穿过霓虹灯照亮的城市，目瞪口呆地看着街上的舞者和小贩。这两部电影都以第二代美国人经历了深刻的成长为结尾：雷切尔获得了自信（以及丈夫），尚气成为了名副其实的超级英雄。<br><br>乍一看， <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>可能看起来并没有偏离这些大纲情节。故事讲述奥黛丽（Audrey）是一个白人家庭收养的中国人，她与洛洛（Lolo）和她朋友的表弟“神枪手”一起去了中国。最初，她来这里是为了做生意，但由于洛洛的刺激和一些滑稽的情况，她最终利用这次旅行找到了她的亲生母亲。 <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>最终为我们提供了一个半开玩笑版本的熟悉蒙太奇，奥黛丽似乎接受了她的任务：这伙人与当地人一起坐在一辆卡车后面，然后奥黛丽像<em>《音乐之声》</em>那样在一个酒吧前旋转。山景，宣示“我爱中国！”这一幕在洛洛祖母家举行的一场喧闹的聚会中达到高潮，中国大家庭张开双臂欢迎朋友们。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/">阅读：请更多带有狂野性爱场景的喜剧</a><br><br>然而， <em>Joy Ride</em>倾向于其过度的感性，并通过眨眼和轻推来提供这些理想化的序列。观众无意将“我心中国”蒙太奇理解为一种简单化的角色发展形式。相反，它是电影更大背景的一部分，推动观众直击内心。首先，奥黛丽对她个人旅程的幸福拥抱是喜剧性的，反映了她的天真。然后，当她最终即将见到她的生母时，她并没有彻底实现自我实现。相反，她得到了关于她的血统的令人惊讶的消息，这改变了她寻找身份的前提。奥黛丽回到美国后并没有顿悟，反而遇到了比离开时更多的麻烦。<br><br>这种复杂的未完成任务的感觉在其他具有类似弧线的电影中也很明显，这些弧线抵制理想化的家园。王璐璐的《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/07/farewell-lulu-wang-movie-review-awkwafina/593464/"><em>别告诉她》</em></a>遵循了这一叙事，欧亚电影制片人制作的小规模电影也遵循这一叙事，例如周大卫的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/02/return-to-seoul-movie-review/673127/"><em>《重返首尔》</em></a>和洪考乌的<em>《季风》</em> 。这些电影与那些脆弱的同类电影之间的主要区别在于，它们能够使用返校节作为情节设计，但又没有明确暗示它将解决角色的所有问题。在<em>《别告诉她》</em>中，故事的重点不再是主角回到中国能给她带来什么，而是更多地关注她跨越国界的悲伤之旅。在<em>《重返首尔》</em>中，一名被收养者的韩国之行被用来毫不妥协地审视她的矛盾心理和鲁莽行为。<em>季风</em>将主角对家的渴望与他对同性恋的渴望联系起来。所有这些电影都拒绝沉迷于愿望的实现。<br><br> <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>也不例外，它为一部淫秽的喜剧带来了微妙的智慧。奥黛丽的核心需求是归属感和接受度。这部电影并没有让她在国外找到它，而是引导她去寻找那些在操场上支持她或支持她完成大学学业的朋友。朝圣之旅会带你回到一直在那里的亲人身边，这也是女孩或男孩旅行叙事中常见的情节。但考虑到<em>欢乐乘车</em>的文化背景，它巧妙地破坏了祖国的比喻。奥黛丽的朋友们是她的救赎，因为他们是同一个复杂的侨民的一部分，并且知道以特定方式努力归属感是什么感觉。洛洛（Lolo）的性积极艺术作品在她的移民父母经营的餐厅里不受欢迎；另一位朋友凯特（Kat）正拼命地向她高度虔诚的中国未婚夫扮演独身者，尽管她的大学过去很不修边幅。这些女性最终不需要寻找某种神话般的归属感——她们已经属于彼此了。通过让角色认识到这一点， <em>《欢乐之旅》</em>放弃了祖国解决一切问题的义务，并强调了我们称之为家的关系的变革力量。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-movie-asia-chinese-diaspora/674717/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-movie-asia-chinese-diaspora/674717/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Drink More Water]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>热浪中补水的注意事项<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/kUl52UotDYjprRiWwOsW33o81Vk=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/survive_a_heatwave_horz_final/original.jpg" alt="水滴和水杯的拼贴画" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>令人痛苦和压抑的酷热并未减弱。如今，随着气温不断打破纪录，三分之一的美国人处于高温警报之下：凤凰城已<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/11/us/phoenix-heat-wave.html">连续两周</a>达到 110 华氏度，而本周末加利福尼亚州死亡谷的气温<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/13/us/california-heat-wave.html">可能会超过</a>130 华氏度的历史最高纪录。<br><br>即使不那么极端的高温也可能是危险的。最近，在德克萨斯州、路易斯安那州、亚利桑那州的一部分和佛罗里达州，都有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/heat-deaths-dome-texas-california-south-d820a8782d3bc15abbe713af81dc7d7f">报道</a>称有人因高温<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.12news.com/article/news/local/hot-temperatures-have-led-to-8-deaths-10-burn-hospitalizations-officials-say-reporting-lags-numbers-will-soar/75-f6367179-0be1-4ced-af85-28c9e4445142">死亡</a>，还有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jun/28/record-setting-texas-heat-sends-hundreds-emergency-rooms">更多</a>人住院治疗。目前热浪造成的死亡人数并不总是很清楚：一份 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02419-z#Sec8">新的报告显示</a><u>，</u>去年夏天欧洲历史性的热浪导致超过 60,000 人死亡。<br><br>理想情况下，您应该尽可能呆在有空调的室内。这不是每个人都可以选择的。另一件要做的事情是保持水分。获得足够液体的重要性怎么强调都不为过，而且常常被低估：上个月，德克萨斯州立法机构禁止地方政府强制建筑工人断水。凤凰城亚利桑那州立大学水合科学实验室主任斯塔夫罗斯·卡沃拉斯告诉我，在炎热的天气下，水合作用“会影响一切”。随着气温持续升高，采取正确措施至关重要。<br><br>严重脱水对你来说真的非常糟糕。您的血容量减少，这会降低您的心脏工作效率。 “你的体温调节能力下降，”卡沃拉斯告诉我，“所以你的体温越来越高。”您可能会感到虚弱或头晕。你的心率上升；变得更难集中注意力。最糟糕的情况是中暑，此时您的身体无法自行冷却，这可能是致命的医疗紧急情况。<br><br>在极端温度下，热损伤发生的速度比您想象的要快。鉴于人体主要是水，你可能会认为还有一些多余的水，但不方便的是，事实并非如此。卡沃拉斯说：“如果你失去了体内 10% 的水分，你就进入了严重的临床脱水区。” “如果你着眼于<em>最佳</em>健康状态，即使只减掉 1% 的体重也会影响你的身体机能。”当身体变热时，有两种基本的自我冷却方式。一是向皮肤输送更多的血液，从而释放身体核心的热量，这也是你在过热时变红的原因。另一个就是出汗。它会从你的身体蒸发，在此过程中，你的身体会失去多余的热量。如果你没有适当补充水分，你就无法有效地给自己降温。与此同时，你的主要冷却机制之一是主动脱水，这意味着目标不仅仅是<em>补充</em>水分，而是保持这种状态。<br><br>卡沃拉斯说，这取决于许多因素，而不是单一的普遍规则，但总的来说，危险区域是“湿度超过 90 度的高湿度”，此时，只要在外面“实际上就很危险”。您在高温下越活跃，天气越热、越潮湿，风险就越大，适当的补水就变得越重要。美国非热浪时期的标准用水目标是男性每天 3.7 升，女性每天 2.7 升。当天气非常非常热时，您需要更多。即使您一天的大部分时间都在空调的幸福中度过，您几乎肯定会在<em>某个</em>时候离开家。<br><br>卡沃拉斯建议您不要试图弄清楚确切的金额应该是多少，而是关注两件事。 “不。 1、让水靠近你。如果你附近有水或任何健康饮料，你最终会喝更多，只是因为它更近，”他说。其次：注意小便的频率——尿液呈浅色，每天六到七次，或者每两到三个小时一次，就很好。休斯顿 UTHealth 麦戈文医学院的运动心脏病专家约翰·希金斯 (John Higgins) 告诉我，你希望它“基本上像夏布利、雷司令、灰比诺或香槟色”。 “如果你发现尿液颜色变深，就像霞多丽或长相思那样，通常意味着你脱水了。”<br><br>某些群体尤其面临风险。老年人、幼儿、孕妇和服用某些药物（例如降压药）的人更容易脱水。这些本身并不要求您摄入<em>额外的</em>液体，只是您需要更加小心，确保摄入足够的液体。<br><br>至于喝什么，作为首选饮料，纯水是无可匹敌的。漂浮着水果片的水有一种感觉就像来自豪华酒店的感觉。碳酸水也很好，你可能无法喝那么多，这是一个潜在的缺点，但“你的胃肠道系统中没有任何机制可以降低苏打水的补水效果，”卡沃拉斯说。你可能想避免喝大量的咖啡——大量的咖啡因是一种利尿剂，希金斯出于同样的原因警告不要喝含糖饮料。 （每天一杯冰咖啡就可以了。）如果您连续数小时大量出汗，那么您可能会喝一些（含糖量较低的）运动饮料。但对于大多数人来说，水仍然是理想的。食物也可以是液体来源：“确保你的饮食富含含水量的蔬菜和水果，”北卡罗来纳大学格林斯博罗分校水合、环境和热量 (HEAT) 主任威廉·亚当斯 (William Adams) 说压力实验室，建议。酒精会导致你<em>失去</em>水分，这绝对没有帮助。<br><br>那里有很多关于水的神话。你能不能太过用力？从技术上讲，水分过多可能会导致电解质失衡，但三位专家都认为，对于大多数人来说，这并不是真正的问题。你可以找到关于在夏天喝热饮的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/thesalt/2012/07/11/156378713/cool-down-with-a-hot-drink-its-not-as-crazy-as-you-think">论据</a>——他们的想法是它们会增加你的出汗量， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/a-hot-drink-on-a-hot-day-can-cool-you-down-1338875/">从而促进降温</a>。但卡沃拉斯强调，你最好喝冷饮，这样可以让你的身体凉爽，他说。在比赛前一刻，马拉松运动员有时会更进一步，喝冰浆来降低体温。对于优质的老式饮用水来说，最好的温度是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261517517_Optimal_Composition_of_Fluid-Replacement_Beverages">50 华氏度</a>左右，大约是水龙头流出的凉水的温度。<br><br>保持水分的最后一个关键是：尽早开始。希金斯说，很多人一直处于轻度脱水状态，无论是否有热浪。 “所以特别是当你早上第一次醒来时，通常你处于脱水状态。”因此，他建议人们一醒来就喝一瓶标准水的量——大约 17 盎司。他说，人们忘记的另一件事是他们在经历了户外活动后回到室内时会发生什么。 “你一直在出汗，”他指出。换句话说：补水，然后<em>继续</em>补水。<br><br>尽管补水很重要，但这并不是什么奇迹。卡沃拉斯说：“这并不意味着你可以说，‘我水分充足，所以我会在 120 度的天气里出去跑步，而且我会没事的，因为我喝了很多酒。’” 。 “这样不行。”尽管如此，它仍然是一个简单但有效的工具。随着像这样的热浪变得更加频繁，更多的人将需要学习如何适应水分。也许充足的水可能是一种反常的安慰：你无法控制无情的炎热，但你可能可以控制水的摄入量。在热浪中，保持半杯水和一杯空水的态度会有所帮助。<br><br><small><em>这个故事是 HHMI 科学和教育媒体集团支持的《大西洋星球》系列的一部分。</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 13:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/the-dos-and-donts-of-Hydrating-in-a-heat-wave/674704/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/07/the-dos-and-donts-of-Hydrating-in-a-heat-wave/674704/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Is a Glass of Wine Harmless? Wrong Question.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>最新的饮酒建议忽视了快乐的价值。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/LhxMO4yoXcC8qZw70hecla-jF4E=/1x0:2444x1374/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_56464858_copy/original.jpg" alt="一个人检查一杯酒的图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>图像/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br>不久前，酒精对你有好处。在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://blog.iwfs.org/2014/08/french-paradox-how-a-60-minutes-segment-transformed-red-wine-consumption-in-america/">1991 年的<i>《60 分钟》</i>节目</a>中，一位法国研究人员<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njm1LkXP2sg">声称</a>，饮用红酒对法国人的健康有益。事实证明，这一论点受到葡萄酒消费群体的欢迎，并促使<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/014067369190542W">学术论文</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/content/310/6988/1165.short">提出</a>红酒消费与心血管疾病之间存在反比关系。科学家甚至提出了一种解释红酒健康的机制理论，其中涉及一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://europepmc.org/article/med/7499059">名为白藜芦醇的</a>化合物。<br><br>其他人很快就对红酒与长寿是否真的存在因果关系的可能性表示怀疑。 “酒精对你有好处”的说法被侵蚀了，在过去的一年里，似乎已经完全崩溃了。许多研究人员现在认为，基本上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/5376552/how-much-alcohol-to-drink-study/"><i>任何</i>数量</a>的酒精都对你有害。 <i>《纽约时报》</i>一月份的一篇文章标题为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/13/well/mind/alcohol-health-effects.html">即使是一点点酒精也会损害你的健康</a>”。因此<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ccsa.ca/canadas-guidance-alcohol-and-health">，包括加拿大政府在内的</a>一些人建议，最安全的选择就是<i>根本</i>不喝酒。<br><br>过量饮酒显然会导致严重的身体和情感问题。这没有争议。然而：<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DkS1pkKpILY">最近的</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/wellness/2023/03/31/moderate-drinking-alcohol-wine-risks/">言论</a>转向禁欲，远远超出了避免大量饮酒的合理建议，并且忽视了快乐的价值。<br><br><a href="http://v/">阅读：每天喝酒几乎肯定不会伤害你</a><br><br>即使在酒精领域之外，一种与快乐无关的健康建议方法现在也很流行，并且正在渗透到公众中，有时会产生荒谬的结果。最近，一位读者问我：<i>有没有关于性高潮对健康有益的数据？</i>我不知道来自随机实验的可靠数据表明，拥有更多的性高潮可以改善健康。无论如何，这不是高潮的意义。高潮的要点在于它们很有趣。我们不需要证明健康益处就可以拥有它们。<br><br>公共卫生建议有时基于“字典式”标准——将对健康的影响放在第一位、第二位和第三位，而忽略其他考虑因素，包括享受。例如，适用于肉类消费的词典标准表明，我们必须始终吃熟透的汉堡，因为这是避免<i>大肠杆菌</i>风险的最佳方法，尽管熟透的汉堡无味。更一般地说，一些公共卫生领域的人避免讨论专制主义带来的意想不到的负面后果。在冠状病毒大流行期间，一些官员强烈主张长期关闭学校，认为让孩子们呆在家里是防止学生和教师在学校传播病毒的唯一方法。从技术意义上来说，这是正确的，但这项建议没有考虑到这些关闭给儿童带来的巨大成本，而这些成本应该与任何好处进行权衡。<br><br>回到酒精问题上，如果现有的最佳证据表明，即使是适度饮酒也会造成<i>巨大</i>危害，那么快乐不可知论可能是有道理的。它不是。我还应该强调，这些数据从根本上来说是有缺陷的，因为我们拥有的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-022-28735-5">最大</a>、最常被引用的研究是观察性的，而不是随机的。而且适量饮酒的人与不适量饮酒的人的特征是不同的。<br><br> 2018 年， <i>《柳叶刀》</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thelancet.com/article/S0140-6736(18)31310-2/fulltext">发表了一项关于饮酒与癌症、心脏病和其他疾病之间联系的综合研究</a>。这是一部非凡的学术著作，结合了之前数百篇论文。研究结果表明，癌症发病率呈上升趋势，尤其是随着饮酒量的增加。但适度饮酒（例如每天一到两杯）的影响<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2018/08/there-is-a-safe-level-of-alcohol/568531/">非常小</a>。对于心脏病，我们看到适度饮酒时风险会<i>降低</i>，而饮酒量较高时风险会增加。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/america-drinking-alone-problem/619017/">摘自2021年7月/8月号：美国存在饮酒问题</a><br><br><i>这些结果都没有令人信服的因果关系</i>。<i> </i>似乎所有的联想——无论是积极的还是消极的——相对于事实都被夸大了。一般来说，当研究人员能够根据某些人口统计差异进行调整时，酒精与健康之间的关系就会变小。这反过来表明，如果他们能够<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/07350015.2016.1227711">针对更多差异进行调整</a>，那么差异还会变得更小。这些关系是否会更小但仍然是正的，或者实际上为零，这是我们无法从现有数据中得知的。<br><br>我们无法最终证明适量饮酒完全是良性的，更不用说有益了。根据我们掌握的数据，适量饮酒似乎也不太可能对您的健康完全“有害”。<br><br>如果您不喜欢或非常不喜欢酒精，那么戒酒标准可能适合您。但很多人确实时不时地喜欢喝一杯：和朋友喝一杯啤酒，夏天喝一杯冰镇桃红葡萄酒，在火炉前喝一杯热棕榈酒，甚至在漫长的烹饪结束时喝一杯白葡萄酒。天。如果我们承认快乐是有价值的，并且数据是混乱的，那么适度标准就更有意义。<br><br>酒精的钟摆与 20 世纪 90 年代相比已经摇摆得太远了。酒精可能不是长寿的关键。但它也不是砷。用《Cookie Monster》的不朽名言来说，它有时也是一种食物。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 14 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/moderate-drinking-heart-disease-cancer/674692/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/moderate-drinking-heart-disease-cancer/674692/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Things Don’t Always Change in a Nice, Gradual Way’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>气候变化现在比以往任何时候都更加真实。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/qc5c_UZcGPaILKxUDy6ePEsgbg4=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/extreme_climate/original.jpg" alt="三张 2023 年夏季戏剧性气候事件的拼接照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大卫·迪·德尔加多/盖蒂；约翰·塔利/华盛顿邮报/盖蒂；阿什思考/彭博社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>追踪所有重叠的气候灾难变得越来越困难。在亚利桑那州凤凰城，气温连续近两周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.azfamily.com/2023/07/12/110-streak-continues-with-hottest-weekend-summer-ahead/">突破110度</a>。佛罗里达州海岸附近的海水正接近<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/12/climate/florida-ocean-temperatures-reefs.html">热水浴缸般的高温</a>，不久之后，海洋热浪可能会覆盖<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://research.noaa.gov/2023/06/28/global-ocean-roiled-by-marine-heatwaves-with-more-on-the-way/">世界一半的海洋</a>。在北部，加拿大<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/International/International/canada-marks-worst-wildfire-season-record/story?id=100474336#:~:text=Wildfires%20have%20burned%2019.5%20million%20acres%20across%20Canada%20this%20year%20so%20far.&amp;text=LONDON%20%2D%2D%20Canada's%20wildfire%20season,19.5%20million%20acres%20so%20far.">有记录以来最严重的野火季节</a>仍在继续，零星的烟雾继续使美国城市窒息，烟雾可能要<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://heatmap.news/climate/wildfire-smoke-2023-aqi-long">到十月才能</a>彻底消散。在东北部，洪水使城镇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/11/us/vermont-flooding-damage-rescues.html">被淹没</a>， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/AlexRuane/status/1678484215036354560?s=20">整条道路</a>被冲毁，火车轨道诡异地<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://weather.com/news/trending/video/floods-leave-train-tracks-hanging-in-vermont">悬浮</a>在 100 英尺高的空中。此外，南极洲的海冰——现在应该正在迅速扩大，因为，记住，那里现在是冬天——可能正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nsidc.org/arcticseaicenews/">失去质量</a>。<br><br>从某种意义上说，这种危机的堆积正是气候科学家所预期的。哥伦比亚大学大气科学家西蒙·李告诉我，全球气温正在以几乎预期的速度上升，自然灾害是这一事实的必然结果。每年发生的情况都会有一些变化，总体而言，今年的情况可能比趋势线预测的情况稍差。但事实是，所有这些灾难至少在某种程度上都与气候变化有关。它让炎热的日子变得更加炎热。使得暴雨更加猛烈。它使景观变得干燥，并为它们点火做好准备。 “我们不再需要进行特定的归因研究”来做出这样的断言，气候学家兼美国宇航局戈达德空间研究所所长加文·施密特告诉我。 “我们已经这样做了 20 年……这离火箭科学还很遥远。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/climate-change-heat-waves-ocean-sea-level-rise/674676/">阅读：沸腾的海洋</a><br><br>但当谈到气候科学时，研究人员“期望”的可能是一个粗略的概念。美国国家航空航天局 (NASA) 气候科学家亚历克斯·鲁恩 (Alex Ruane) 告诉我：“我们知道我们所走的总体道路，但事情并不总是以良好、渐进的方式发生变化。”尽管全球形势正在以主要模型预测的速度恶化，但更具体的局部变化可能会令人惊讶。从本质上讲，气候变化是一种破坏稳定的力量：其影响是不可预测的。例如，南极海冰的总表面积目前比一年中这个时候的平均值<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nsidc.org/arcticseaicenews/">小四个标准</a>差以上。这不仅打破了自 20 世纪 70 年代开始测量以来的记录；这<em>打破了</em>记录。为什么现在会发生这种情况——以及它最终会成为一个可怕的昙花一现还是永久的状态——仍然是一个悬而未决的问题。同样，科学家们尚未完全了解气候变化如何影响天气系统在全球范围内的移动方式。一场风暴可能会从遭受干旱的地区转移到一个已经湿透的城镇，或者灼热的气氛可能会在一个地方停止，正如我们在凤凰城上空的热穹所看到的那样。<br><br>即使这些灾难确实按照预期发生，与我交谈的科学家们表示，他们注意到美国人讨论这些灾难的方式发生了变化。 “人们不再用未来时态谈论气候变化，”鲁安说。 “他们正在用现在时谈论气候变化。”他们中越来越多的人有关于气候灾难的个人故事。灾难不再被视为预兆；它们只是被理解为事物本来的样子。 “These are not canaries in the coal mine,” Schmidt said. “The canaries died a long time ago.”<br><br> Back when he worked at <em>The Atlantic</em> , my former colleague Robinson Meyer would end his weekly newsletter with a section called “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2021/04/an-outdated-idea-is-still-shaping-climate-policy/618652/">Someone Else&#39;s Weather</a> ,” because, as he put it, “the climate is someone else&#39;s weather.” I always took this to mean that the abstraction we refer to as the climate is a concrete, imminent reality for someone, <em>somewhere</em> . It&#39;s the sky above their head, the earth beneath their feet, the feeling of the air around them.<br><br> This year&#39;s accumulating catastrophes reinforce this formulation, but they also take it one step further. The heat and the fires and the melting and the floods all contribute to a growing sense that climate change is happening right here and now—that the climate truly has become the weather. We <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-dome-southwest-arizona/674689/">stay in</a> because it&#39;s hot. We take a different route to work because the roads have been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/cavendish-vermont-climate-change-storm-new-england/674682/">washed out</a> . We adjust our plans because of wildfire smoke in the same way that we&#39;ve always done for bouts of lightning and rain. More and more, the climate is not someone else&#39;s weather. It&#39;s our own.<br><br> Hanna Rosin speaks with the climate writer Emma Pattee on how extreme heat is already changing our kids&#39; summers. Listen to <em>Radio Atlantic</em> : <br><br><iframe class="lazyload" data-include="module:theatlantic/js/utils/iframe-resizer" data-src="https://playlist.megaphone.fm/?e=ATL5863360533" frameborder="0" height="200" scrolling="no" title="embedded interactive content" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <em>Subscribe here: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/sorry-honey-its-too-hot-for-camp/id1258635512?i=1000619524121">Apple Podcasts</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/sorry-honey-its-too-hot-for-camp/id1258635512?i=1000619524121"> </a>|<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://open.spotify.com/playlist/4PgNKjRJJWlaV6zuNr69BO">Spotify</a> | <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.stitcher.com/show/radio-atlantic">Stitcher</a> | <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://podcasts.google.com/feed/aHR0cHM6Ly9mZWVkcy5tZWdhcGhvbmUuZm0vcmFkaW9hdGxhbnRpYw">Google Podcasts</a> | <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pca.st/ccxU">Pocket Casts</a></em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 13 Jul 2023 21:39:14 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-climate-crises-natural-disasters/674700/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-climate-crises-natural-disasters/674700/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[More Comedies With Wild Sex Scenes, Please]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> <em>Joy Ride</em> and <em>Bottoms</em> are reviving R-rated raunch at the theaters, and upending<strong> </strong>tropes about women in filthy romps. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/fluHdxJckPQoL_xXx_cTDH4isq0=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/rauncy_comedy_2/original.jpg" alt="Characters from the movies “Bottoms” and “Joy Ride,” side by side" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo-illustration by The Atlantic. Sources: Ed Araquel / Lionsgate; MGM</figcaption></figure> An outrageous film requires outrageous writing—and in the case of <em>Joy Ride</em> , outrageous brainstorming sessions. When the comedy&#39;s writers, Teresa Hsiao and Cherry Chevapravatdumrong, were working on a sex scene involving a Theragun and a basketball, they figured they should test out the sequence themselves. (Adding unusual props meant untangling some complicated physics.) So Hsiao took a basketball, placed it between her legs, laid down on her back, and Chevapravatdumrong Theragun-ed away. “We&#39;re <em>authentic</em> … I mean, it&#39;s like, &#39;Write what you know,&#39;” Chevapravatdumrong deadpanned when we spoke over Zoom last month. “So we had to know it first.”<br><br> The road-trip comedy, now in theaters, juggles tones and locations as it tracks the journey of Audrey (played by Ashley Park), a lawyer who travels to China with a trio of mismatched friends to close a business deal and search for her birth mother. The film is part of a booming summer slate of sex comedies, a once-dominant genre in recent need of resuscitation. <em>No Hard Feelings</em> , which topped the box office when it was released in June, followed Maddie ( <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/06/no-hard-feelings-movie-review/674510/">a screwball Jennifer Lawrence</a> ), a 32-year-old Uber driver who pretends to date a rich 19-year-old so that she can save her family home. <em>Bottoms</em> , a movie from <em>Shiva Baby</em> writer-director Emma Seligman about two teenagers who would do <em>anything</em> to sleep with their high school&#39;s hottest cheerleaders—in this case, starting a female fight club just to approach them—hits screens in August.<br><br> Of these, <em>Joy Ride</em> —which, aside from the Theragun incident, includes a concussion-inducing threesome and a “WAP” needle drop—may be the most explicit, especially when compared with the surprisingly sweet <em>No Hard Feelings</em> . But all three movies upend tropes about women in sex comedies and, in a post-#MeToo and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/06/will-sex-scenes-survive-the-pandemic/613156/">pandemic-tested landscape</a> , challenge the notion that depicting the changing social mores around sex can&#39;t be fun. On top of that, they&#39;re plain satisfying to watch—especially in a theater, gasping and gaping at the most ridiculous moments with a packed crowd. The return of R-rated raunch to cinemas “really feels like a moment for humanity,” Hsiao marveled, “in an insane way.” The genre is much more than a collection of gross-out jokes. Such films reflect how attitudes about sex—that most foundational yet taboo impulse that comes with being human—have evolved.<br><br> Of all the ingredients necessary to make a good modern sex comedy, a layer of resonant feeling may be the most essential. Just look at the films that the writers of <em>Joy Ride</em> and <em>Bottoms</em> told me were some of their touchstones. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/09/the-remarkable-rise-of-tiffany-haddish/538872/"><em>Girls Trip</em></a> &#39;s lead character is trying to survive an obviously broken marriage. <em>Bridesmaids</em> is fueled by its protagonist&#39;s fear of being left behind as her friends embrace adult life. <em>Superbad</em> is about the separation anxiety that comes with graduating and going to college. Finding the emotional story for <em>Bottoms</em> , Seligman explained over the phone, made the movie “a little bit more grounded than we initially intended it to be,” with raunch and absurdity forming the Trojan horse for a deeper plot.<br><br> Consider the wildest scenes in <em>Joy Ride</em> . When Kat (Stephanie Hsu), Audrey&#39;s friend from college, accidentally exposes an extravagantly lewd tattoo on her nether region, the reveal both shocks and changes the dynamics among the friend group by undercutting Kat&#39;s holier-than-thou attitude. When the buttoned-up, careerist Audrey has a wild threesome, the chaos delights because she&#39;s finally cut loose. “If [a scene] is based in a grounded character beat,” Chevapravatdumrong said, “it&#39;s not just a joke that&#39;s like, &#39;Ah, we&#39;re being disgusting for the sake of being disgusting.&#39;”<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/06/no-hard-feelings-movie-review/674510/">Read: Thank goodness for Jennifer Lawrence&#39;s R-rated rom-com</a><br><br> For better or worse, <em>Joy Ride</em> and <em>Bottoms</em> must also deal with the pressure of being considered groundbreaking for Hollywood. The former is the first studio sex comedy to be led by an Asian ensemble. The latter is the rare teen-centric project to treat queer desire, especially between female partners, with both gravity and riotous humor. Making sex a prominent part of these stories while incorporating the thoroughly unsexy subject of representation created an unusual conundrum during the writing process. “I don&#39;t know if I&#39;d use the word <em>prudish</em> ,” Seligman told me, “but I do think we have been in a weird sort of turning point where at least I feel, as a female director [making] movies about sex, extra cautious.”<br><br> When I bring up the fact that <em>Joy Ride</em> is considered the first film of its kind, Hsiao and Chevapravatdumrong chuckle; they&#39;ve heard it said so often, it&#39;s become somewhat of an inside joke for the cast and crew. By treating the subject of their characters&#39; race as a source of humor—but not the butt of the joke—Hsiao said they hoped their script would be “funny to a wide group of people.” In one scene, the friends pretend to be members of a K-pop band, rewarding stans who can appreciate the nuances of the parody while also wringing laughs from the ensemble&#39;s extreme commitment and subsequent failure to convince anyone that they&#39;re highly trained entertainers. “[If] someone who maybe isn&#39;t as familiar with Asian culture comes in and laughs really hard at our movie, but then feels like they have learned a little bit of something along the way, that&#39;s amazing,” Chevapravatdumrong said. The point, Hsiao added, is to invite viewers to learn more if they don&#39;t get a punch line right away.<br><br> <em>Bottoms</em> takes a different approach. The film tells the story of two best friends, PJ (Rachel Sennott) and Josie ( <em>The Bear</em> ’s Ayo Edebiri), who, after a rumor spreads about them spending their summer in prison, capitalize on their new tough-gal reputations by starting a fight club. They&#39;re supposed to teach members self-defense, but the whole thing&#39;s a ruse to bait their crushes into spending time with them. The high-concept plot contributes to the film&#39;s hyper-precise tone, which draws inspiration not only from raunchy movies, but also from action-infused romps, black comedies, and satires in the vein of <em>Heathers</em> , <em>Shaun of the Dead</em> , and <em>But I&#39;m a Cheerleader</em> . PJ and Josie&#39;s club is a ludicrously bloody operation—bombs are involved, and the body count rises as the film goes on—powered by a script that piles on multilayered jokes as cheeky as they are cutting.<br><br> Take the scene that Seligman told me has been surprising viewers at screenings. Thrilled that their cheerleader marks have joined their club, PJ and Josie attempt to foster deeper relationships by having everyone share their traumas. They ask the members to raise their hand if they&#39;ve been sexually assaulted, making a point to add that “gray-area stuff counts too.” Every member does so in response, and the moment is equally somber and funny. PJ and Josie, after all, didn&#39;t intend for their venture to be empowering. They were just horny, but pursuing an iota of emotional connection with the other girls inadvertently led to exposing hard truths.<br><br> Seligman told me she suspects that the audience&#39;s laughter comes from the scene&#39;s unexpected frankness. “Sex is a huge part of our culture and our world,” she said. “If we can&#39;t make movies that make us laugh about a subject that affects all of us, from our perspective, it feels incredibly inhibiting … So much of the time, female characters in sex comedies are just learning [about sex], and are like, &#39;Oh my God, this is crazy, what&#39;s a vibrator?&#39;” <em>Bottoms</em> rejects that naivete. By making its most risqué jokes with complete sincerity, the film pokes fun at the preposterousness of high-school dynamics while reminding viewers that teenage girls have rarely been portrayed realistically in similar movies that came before it.<br><br> The release of these films is enough to demonstrate that a fresh perspective in a familiar genre goes a long way in widening cultural vocabulary. But the biggest thrill of watching them, especially within weeks of one another, comes from seeing how they vary. <em>No Hard Feelings</em> , the tamest entry, is a showcase for a movie star who&#39;s clearly been itching for something lively and low-stakes. <em>Joy Ride</em> packs in a dizzying amount of crass jokes and flamboyant set pieces that show off the richness of its characters. And <em>Bottoms</em> &#39; over-the-top premise allows it to make trenchant observations about youthful lust. For Chevapravatdumrong, Hsiao, and Seligman, writing a sex comedy has been cathartic—an endeavor, as Chevapravatdumrong put it, that “came naturally” because she was writing with the sense of humor she&#39;d long wished to see more of on-screen. “We didn&#39;t have to think about” how raunchy to be, she said, “because that&#39;s who we are.” For all the outrageousness, the writers are tapping into a softer human instinct: to connect over a little laughter.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 13 Jul 2023 14:29:39 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Learn a Foreign Language Before It’s Too Late]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> AI translators may seem wondrous but they also erode a major part of what it is to be human. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/5M15ZusU0gok3jCRmFL6TZo4VZE=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/languages_illo_horiz/original.jpg" alt="“你好”一词的图像：被翻译成西班牙语、法语和意大利语，被用英语书写的“你好”一词遮盖了。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ben Kothe / The Atlantic</figcaption></figure> To me, AI&#39;s scariest aspect is the so-called singularity—the threat of a runaway intelligence explosion leaving humanity in the dust. But today&#39;s state of the art in artificial intelligence is already auguring smaller but still shattering scenarios.<br><br> Some people so deeply yearn to climb Mount Everest that they prepare for years, spend vast sums of money, exhaust themselves for weeks in the climb itself, and repeatedly put their lives at risk. Does that sound like you? Or would you rather just land on its summit in a helicopter and feast yourself on the great view? And what about scaling the <em>metaphorical</em> Everest of a foreign language? Two small episodes in my life in the past month led me to serious musings along these lines.<br><br> Two weeks ago, I watched, for the first time ever, a video of myself back in 2018 in Hangzhou, China, as I struggled mightily for three minutes to make a few off-the-cuff remarks to about 20 young people from Shanghai who belonged to a club of AI enthusiasts. They had traveled 200 miles to Hangzhou to meet me for dinner, and for two and a half hours we had spoken only English together, but toward the evening&#39;s end they asked me if I wouldn&#39;t mind saying something very brief <em>in Chinese</em> for those club members who hadn&#39;t been able to make the trip. Uh-oh! Panic city! Even though I had devoted many arduous years to the study of Chinese (always thinking of the daunting phrase “Learning Chinese is a five-year lesson in humility” as a ridiculous understatement), and had worked like the devil during the previous three months in Hangzhou, I was caught way off guard by their request and, although in the end I obliged them, I felt super jittery while doing so. Shortly thereafter they sent me the video, but for all these years I hadn&#39;t dared to look at even the opening few seconds of it, so scared was I of seeing myself linguistically stumble all over the place.<br><br> But what I saw, when I finally dared to watch myself very recently, was surprising. I saw a person who was not just struggling hard to express himself in a very difficult alien tongue, but who was actually doing a fairly decent job of it, while at the same time coming across as insecure and vulnerable, yet courageously willing to take the bull by the horns. In short, today&#39;s me felt proud of my 2018 self! Since that day five years ago, sadly, my once-okay Chinese has gone to the dogs, and today I couldn&#39;t give a three-minute talk in Chinese to save my life, so I&#39;m thrilled to have proof that at one time in my life, I was actually able to wing it, actually able to give a tiny “talk” in Chinese, even if only a three-minute one.<br><br> So that&#39;s the first episode; here&#39;s the other. A few weeks ago, my very dear Italian friend Benedetto Scimemi passed away, and I spent hours writing heartfelt emails of condolence to all the members of his family. It happens that I lived in Italy for nearly three years and, on top of that, my two children and I have spoken Italian for 30 years as our family language, so my Italian is very fluent and comfortable—but, even so, it is not the Italian of a native speaker. In writing those difficult and emotional emails, I was constantly adjusting my words and phrases, lovingly remembering Benedetto and all the wonderful things we had done together, and pushing my Italian to its very limits. It took me perhaps two or three times as long as it would have taken me in English, but I did it with all my heart. I looked up lots of words in the big, heavy dictionary that I always keep right by my computer, and I felt my words were really <em>me</em> ; my caring concentration on each and every turn of phrase made them mirror my feelings of love for my late friend in the most intensely personal way. Once again I was proud of myself and of the manner in which, over decades, I had come to be able to express myself clearly, strongly, and with a deeply felt voice in a tongue that was not my mother tongue.<br><br> Over the course of my life, I have studied lots of languages to various degrees, and I jokingly call myself “pilingual,” meaning that if you were to add up the fractional levels of mastery of all the languages I&#39;ve tackled, you&#39;d get a number a bit over three, counting English as one, French as 0.8, Italian as 0.7, and going down from there, with Chinese as maybe 0.3, at its apex (probably just 0.1 today).<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/generative-ai-human-culture-philosophy/674165/">Read: The coming human renaissance</a><br><br> Leaving aside my native tongue, I have devoted many thousands of hours of my life to seven languages (French, Italian, German, Swedish, Russian, Polish, and Chinese)—sometimes flailing desperately and sometimes finding enormous gratification. But through thick and thin, I have relentlessly bashed my head against each of those languages for years, because I love each one&#39;s sounds, words, intonation patterns, idioms, proverbs, poetry, songs, and so on. It&#39;s hard to think of anything else, in the world of the mind, that has pulled me as intensely as my craving to internalize the magic logic of an alien tongue from a faraway place.<br><br> But today we have Google Translate. Today we have DeepL. Today we have ChatGPT—and so on. There&#39;s no need for me to list all the powerful technologies that allow anyone today—a monolingual American, say, who has never devoted a single moment to learning, say, Chinese—to write fluent passages in Chinese. Today it&#39;s a piece of cake to send an email in a tongue you don&#39;t know a word of. You just click on “Translate” and presto! There it is! Or at least, there it is, in a certain sense. Assuming that there are no egregious translational blunders (which there often still are), what you are sending off is slick but soulless text.<br><br> Just imagine if the Shanghai AI club had asked me to say a few words for the club&#39;s absent members not in Chinese but in English, and then, while I was speaking, they ran my English words through a speech-transcribing app, then a translation app, then a speech-producing app, so that my English words came out <em>, in real time,</em> in Chinese. (In fact, if this were happening today, the speech-producing app could even use my very own voice, speaking with a perfect Mandarin accent!) Had the club gone that techie-type route, which they might well have liked to do, we could have bypassed any need for me to struggle and strain to express myself in their tongue. For both me and the club members, it would have been effortless.<br><br> However, in this scenario, the video watchers would be deprived of coming to know key aspects of the very human personality of their invitee. They would not see Douglas Hofstadter (known in Chinese as “Hou Daoren”) groping for Chinese words, would not witness his insecurity, his vulnerability, or, for that matter, his dogged determination; they would merely see an American casually speaking in his native tongue (though what they would <em>hear</em> is perfect Chinese); they would get no sense for the <em>real</em> me, who had devoted thousands of hours, spread out over many years, to grappling with their native tongue. My <em>ideas</em> would come across, more or less, but not those hidden aspects of my <em>self</em> .<br><br> But let me play devil&#39;s advocate for a moment. Today&#39;s AI technology allows people of different cultures to communicate instantly and effortlessly with one another.哇！ Isn&#39;t that a centuries-long dream come true, weaving the world ever more tightly together? Isn&#39;t it a wonderful miracle? Isn&#39;t the soon-to-arrive world where everyone can effortlessly speak every language just glorious?<br><br> Some readers will certainly say “yes,” but I would say “no.” In fact, I see this looming scenario as a great tragedy. I see it as the beginning of the end of the age-old tradition of learning foreign languages—not only here in America, but even in lands like Holland and Sweden, fabled for their citizens&#39; near-universal mastery of several tongues. The problem is that people of all cultures instinctively follow the path of least resistance.<br><br> Why would anyone want to devote thousands of hours to learning a foreign language if, by contrast, they could simply talk into their cellphone and it would instantly spit out “the same message” in any language of their choice, in their own voice, and with a perfect accent to boot? Who wouldn&#39;t want to be able to have complex conversations with anyone they wish, in any country, no matter what language it involves? Why bother to take countless courses in Chinese and still feel deeply inadequate in it when, in a flash, you can communicate not only in Chinese but also in French, Hungarian, Swahili, and so on?<br><br> Suppose I had composed my condolences to Benedetto&#39;s family in English and had then run them through a translation program such as DeepL. The words would have come out very differently from what I wrote in Italian. When I was <em>writing</em> in Italian, I was <em>thinking</em> in Italian, not in English. I was using words and phrases that I have made my own over decades, by having countless intimate conversations with close Italian friends (such as Benedetto himself), by reading hundreds of children&#39;s books in Italian to my kids when they were little tykes, by listening hundreds of times to CDs of lilting Italian songs from the 1930s, by devouring Italian newspapers, by giving untold dozens of lectures in Italian, by watching scores of old Italian movies, by memorizing a few Italian poems, and so on. All that unique flavor, reflecting the myriad idiosyncratic pathways by which I lovingly internalized the Italian language, would be missing from an email that I composed in English and that was instantly converted into Italian by a machine.<br><br> You might say that such a loss is a small price to pay—a <em>teeny</em> price to pay!—for the amazing luxury of being able to produce flawless, flowing emails in a hundred different languages, the luxury of being able to give lectures in real time in a hundred different languages, and so forth and so on. Well, I would reply that the “you” who is “writing” or “speaking” so fluently in all these different languages is not <em>you</em> at all. It is, rather, a deepfake version (or a set of deepfake versions) of you.<br><br> When I was in the roughest times in my endless battles with the Chinese language, I often wished that I could just get an injection that would make me perfectly fluent in Chinese in a flash. How wonderful it would be to be able, at last, to understand everyone around me, to say anything I wanted to say, and so on! But when I thought about it for only a few seconds, I realized that after getting such an injection, I would not feel <em>proud</em> of having learned Chinese by struggling for many years. My instant fluency in Chinese would, in that case, be a trivial acquisition rather than a precious goal obtained thanks to immense hard work. It would mean nothing to me, emotionally. It would be like arriving at the summit of Everest in a helicopter. It would be like taking a new wonder drug that hugely boosted my muscles and hugely sped up my reflexes, making me (even at age 78!) suddenly able to run faster than anyone else in the world. Next thing you know, this old geezer would be winning a gold medal in the Olympic 400 meters. But big deal! “My” gold medal would be a hollow victory proving nothing about my athletic abilities. It would be purely the result of technological cheating. Likewise, my Chinese-fluency injection would be a hollow victory, because “my” Chinese would not in any way represent my very human, very fallible, but also very determined mind and spirit.<br><br> When, in my teenage years, I was striving so passionately to learn French, I sometimes wished that I had just grown up in France with my American parents, so that both French and English were 100 percent native to me. But when I thought about it more carefully, I realized that the reason I was so in love with French was precisely that it was <em>not</em> my mother tongue, and that if it had been, then I wouldn&#39;t be able to hear it in anything like the same way I heard it <em>as an outsider.</em><br><br> Of course, over my six-plus decades of speaking French, I have become less and less of an outsider to it, but still I have somehow preserved the intense love that came from confronting the huge challenge of <em>making French my own</em> in my teenage years, as opposed to simply imbibing it like mother&#39;s milk, as a small child. And I am oh so proud of myself if, after half an hour&#39;s conversation, my native-French interlocutor is startled to learn that I did not grow up speaking French. By dint of intense concentration over decades, I&#39;ve <em>earned</em> that supreme compliment, and knowing I&#39;ve reached that long-dreamed-for level thanks to my years of really hard work is as great a feeling as any I have ever had.<br><br> Today&#39;s young people (even in Holland and Sweden) who grow up with translation software, however, will not be lured in the same way that I, as a teenager, was lured by the fantastic, surrealistic goal of internalizing another language. They won&#39;t feel the slightest temptation to devote a major fraction of their lives to slowly and arduously acquiring the sounds, vocabulary, grammar, and cultural richness of another language. To them, someone with my self-punishing attitude would seem hopelessly wedded to the past. Why on earth cling to riding a horse or a bicycle for transportation, when you can drive a car (not to mention flying in an airplane)? What&#39;s the point of going super slowly when you can go superfast? Okay, okay, on a horse or bicycle you&#39;ll see the scenery a bit better, but is it really worth it, when you can cross an entire continent in hours or days, instead of in weeks or months?<br><br> The question comes down to why we humans use language at all. Isn&#39;t the purpose of language just the communication of facts? If so, then why not simply go for maximizing the number of facts transferred per second? Well, to me, this sounds like a shockingly utilitarian and pragmatic description of what I view as a perpetually astonishing and quasi-magical phenomenon that lies at the very core of conscious life.<br><br> When I speak any language, as all my friends know well, I am always searching for the most appropriate word or idiom, frequently hesitating, stumbling, or suddenly changing course midstream; constantly joking by playing with ambiguity; having fun by putting on droll accents and personas, not to mention coming out with puns (some lovely, some lousy); using alliterative phrases; concocting new words on the fly; making accidental mistakes and laughing at myself; committing deliberate grammatical errors; unconsciously blending idioms and thus creating delightful new turns of phrase; tossing in words from other languages left and right; citing proverbs and quoting snippets of poetry; mixing metaphors; etc., etc. Speaking any language, for me, is a living, dynamic process that is permeated by my own unique humanness, with all its frailties and strengths. How is all of this wildly bubbling richness in Language A going to be mirrored in real time in Language B by a mechanical device that has nothing of those qualities driving it, that has no sense of humor, that has no understanding of irony or self-mockery, that has no awareness of how phrases are unconsciously blended, and so on?<br><br> For me, using language is the very essence of being human. When I speak, I am communicating not only <em>facts</em> , but a <em>way of being</em> . Through my word choices and subtle intonations and tiny hesitations and droll puns and dumb errors (and so on), I am revealing <em>who I am.</em> I am not a <em>persona</em> , but a <em>person</em> .<br><br> Today, though, it strikes me as possible—in fact, quite likely—that humans are collectively going to knuckle under and throw in the towel as far as foreign languages are concerned. Are we language users going to obsequiously hand over all engagement with other tongues to chatbots? Will young people in the coming decades share my youthful ardent desire to tackle towering linguistic Everests demanding long years of dedication? Or will they opt for the helicopter/chatbot pathway, preferring their linguistic lives to be struggle-free? If everything we might ever wish for is just handed to us gratis on a silver platter, then what, I wonder, is the purpose of living?<br><br> As my friend David Moser put it, what may soon go down the drain forever, thanks to these new AI technologies, is the precious gift that one can gain only by immersing oneself deeply in another culture and thereby acquiring an entirely new set of ways of looking at the world. It&#39;s a gift that can&#39;t help but turn any human being into a far richer and broader one. But David fears that it may soon become as rare as hen&#39;s teeth. And, I might add, David knows perfectly whereof he speaks, because in his 30s he recklessly threw himself into the bustling, boiling cauldron of China and its mysterious languages, and after long years of tenaciously clambering up its nearly vertical slopes (sorry for the mixed metaphor!), he emerged as a marvelously fluent speaker of Chinese, able to come out with breathtakingly witty puns on the fly and to do stand-up comedy on national television, not to mention hosting his own weekly TV show, in Chinese, about little-known facets of Beijing.<br><br> To Mo Dawei, as David is known in China, it&#39;s incredibly depressing to contemplate the profound impoverishment of people&#39;s mental and emotional lives that is looming just around every corner of the globe, thanks to the slick seductiveness of AI translation apps, insidiously creeping their way into ordinary people&#39;s lives and sapping their desire to make other tongues their own.<br><br> When children first hear the sounds of another language, they can&#39;t help but wonder: <em>What in the world would it feel like to speak that language?</em> Such eager childlike curiosity might seem universal and irrepressible. But what if that human curiosity is suddenly snuffed out forever by the onrushing tsunami of AI? When we collectively abandon the age-old challenge of learning the languages of other lands, when we relinquish that challenge to ultrarapid machines that have no inner life of their own but are able to give us fluent but fake facades in other languages, then we will have lost a major part of what it is to be human and alive.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 13 Jul 2023 13:56:56 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/the-terrible-downside-of-ai-language-translation/674687/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/the-terrible-downside-of-ai-language-translation/674687/</item></channel></rss>